'''Brahim Abdelkader Díaz''' ({{langx|ar|إبراهيم عبد القادر دياز}}; born 3 August 1999), also known mononymously as '''Brahim''', is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as an [[attacking midfielder]] or [[Winger (association football)|winger]] for [[La Liga]] club [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]. Born in Spain, he plays for the [[Morocco national football team|Morocco national team]].

Coming through the ranks at [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], Brahim had started to break through into the first team when he was signed by Real Madrid in 2019. After three successful seasons on loan at [[AC Milan]] where he was part of the [[Serie A]] winning team of 2021-22, Brahim returned to Madrid in 2023 where he became a consistent first team regular, winning the La Liga and the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] in his first full season.

Brahim initially represented Spain at junior level, before making his senior debut against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] in 2021 where he also scored. Following this Brahim decided to change his representative nationality to Morocco. He received his first call-up for Morocco in 2024, and was part of the team that subsequently won the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].

==Early life==
Brahim was born in Málaga, Spain to a Spanish mother and a [[Riffians|Moroccan-Riffian]] father.<ref>{{citation |title=El padre cazatalentos del 'merengue' Brahim Díaz|date=21 January 2019 |url=https://www.elmundo.es/cronica/2019/01/21/5c38f99721efa0296a8b4701.html |access-date=16 October 2025 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-10 |title=حصري: تفاصيل تسجيل ابراهيم دياز بمحكمة الناظور للحصول على الجنسية المغربية - زنقة 20 رياضة |url=https://sport.rue20.com/%d8%ad%d8%b5%d8%b1%d9%8a-%d8%aa%d9%81%d8%a7%d8%b5%d9%8a%d9%84-%d8%aa%d8%b3%d8%ac%d9%8a%d9%84-%d8%a7%d8%a8%d8%b1%d8%a7%d9%87%d9%8a%d9%85-%d8%af%d9%8a%d8%a7%d8%b2-%d8%a8%d9%85%d8%ad%d9%83%d9%85%d8%a9.html |access-date=2026-01-04}}</ref> He grew up in [[Málaga]], but moved to [[Manchester]] at age 16, as he was signed by [[Manchester City F.C. EDS and Academy|Manchester City's youth academy]].<ref>{{citation |title=Abdelkader l'hispano marocain |date=14 December 2017 |url=https://www.africatopsports.com/2017/12/14/abdelkader-diaz-lhispano-marocain-prefere-roja-aux-lions-de-latlas/ |access-date=23 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200723135112/https://www.africatopsports.com/2017/12/14/abdelkader-diaz-lhispano-marocain-prefere-roja-aux-lions-de-latlas/ |archive-date=23 July 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Manchester City===
[[File:FC Salzburg gegen Manchester City FC (U19 8. Februar 2017) 10.jpg|left|thumb|235x235px|Brahim with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2017]]
Brahim began his club career at his hometown club [[Málaga CF|Málaga]], before moving to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 2015 as a 16-year-old for an initial £200,000 fee.<ref name=MCOP>{{cite web |url=https://www.mancity.com/brahim-diaz |title=Brahim Diaz |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |access-date=28 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126050950/https://www.mancity.com/brahim-diaz |archive-date=26 January 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ducker |first=James |title=Manchester City's global scouting mission pays off with 'mind-blowing' talent |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/04/21/manchester-citys-global-scouting-mission-pays-off-with-mind-blow/ |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=21 April 2016 |access-date=28 January 2018 |archive-date=23 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180923012106/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2016/04/21/manchester-citys-global-scouting-mission-pays-off-with-mind-blow/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 September 2016, Díaz made his first-team debut for City, coming on as an 80th-minute [[substitute (association football)|substitute]] to replace [[Kelechi Iheanacho]] in an [[EFL Cup]] tie against [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Swansea City 1–2 Manchester City |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37357877 |website=BBC Sport |date=21 September 2016 |access-date=30 December 2016 |archive-date=21 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321163057/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37357877 |url-status=live }}</ref> Five days later, he signed his first professional contract with City, for three years.<ref>{{cite web |title=Brahim Diaz signs new deal |url=http://www.mancity.com/News/First-Team/2016/09/26/brahim-diaz-pens-first-professional-contract-with-city/1474891101354 |publisher=Manchester City F.C. |date=26 September 2016 |access-date=30 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221200734/https://www.mancity.com/news/first-team/2016/09/26/brahim-diaz-pens-first-professional-contract-with-city/1474891101354 |archive-date=21 December 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

On 21 November 2017, Brahim made his [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut against [[Feyenoord]] in a [[2017–18 UEFA Champions League|group stage]] match, coming on in injury time for [[Raheem Sterling]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester City 1–0 Feyenoord |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42055934 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=25 November 2017 |archive-date=24 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171124202030/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42055934 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 19 December 2017, Brahim made his first club start, playing for 88 minutes against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Leicester City 1–1 Manchester City (3–4 pens) |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42318865 |website=BBC Sport |date=19 December 2017 |access-date=21 December 2017 |archive-date=22 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222180418/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42318865 |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his [[Premier League]] debut on 20 January 2018, in a 3–1 victory over [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Critchley |first=Mark |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/manchester-city-3-newcastle-united-1-match-report-goals-sergio-aguero-jacob-murphy-a8170146.html |title=Sergio Aguero hits a perfect hat-trick as Manchester City end Newcastle's acrimonious week on a sour note |newspaper=The Independent |date=20 January 2018 |access-date=27 January 2018 |archive-date=27 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127003638/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/manchester-city-3-newcastle-united-1-match-report-goals-sergio-aguero-jacob-murphy-a8170146.html |url-status=live }}</ref> and on 13 May, he received a winner's medal after appearing sporadically in four more league games over the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-city-foden-diaz-medal-14652426 |title=Man City fans loved seeing Phil Foden make Premier League history |last=Fay |first=Richard |date=13 May 2018 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |access-date=14 May 2018 |archive-date=14 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514213843/https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/man-city-foden-diaz-medal-14652426 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 5 August 2018, Brahim played the final 15 minutes in place of [[Phil Foden]] a 2–0 win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the [[2018 FA Community Shield]].<ref name=shield>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44995783 |title=Chelsea 0–2 Manchester City |first=Chris |last=Bevan |website=BBC Sport |date=5 August 2018 |access-date=5 August 2018 |archive-date=20 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820135641/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44995783 |url-status=live }}</ref> Later that season, Brahim would score his first career goal for City, netting both times in a 2–0 win over [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 1 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11938/11542190/manchester-city-2-0-fulham-brahim-diaz-scores-twice-in-carabao-cup-win|title= Diaz double puts City into quarters |publisher=SkySports Sport|access-date=27 May 2026}}</ref>

===Real Madrid===
Following intense transfer speculation and with his contract with Manchester City due to expire in June 2019, Díaz joined [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] on 6 January, for a transfer fee of £15.5&nbsp;million (€17&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jackson |first1=Jamie |title=Brahim Díaz on verge of joining Real Madrid from Manchester City for £15.5m |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jan/05/brahim-diaz-real-madrid-manchester-city-transfer-news |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=6 January 2019 |archive-date=6 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406184408/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jan/05/brahim-diaz-real-madrid-manchester-city-transfer-news |url-status=live }}</ref> Díaz put pen to paper on a 6 year deal running through 2025 with add-ons which could potentially see the value of the transfer rise to £22&nbsp;million (€24&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/noticias/2019/01/comunicado-oficial-brahim-diaz|language=es|title=Official Statement: Brahim Díaz|publisher=Real Madrid CF|access-date=6 January 2019|archive-date=29 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191129072410/https://www.realmadrid.com/noticias/2019/01/comunicado-oficial-brahim-diaz|url-status=live}}</ref> The transfer also included clauses which stipulated a 15 percent sell-on fee to be received by City, rising all the way up to 40 percent should Díaz be sold to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lilzino|first1=John|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/manchester-city-united-clause-brahim-diaz-transfer-real-madrid-a8712881.html|title=Brahim Díaz: Manchester City put anti-United clause in Real Madrid transfer to prevent Old Trafford move|date=5 January 2019|newspaper=The Independent|access-date=6 January 2019|archive-date=7 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107083733/https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/manchester-city-united-clause-brahim-diaz-transfer-real-madrid-a8712881.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2018–20: First season in Spain and La Liga title====
He made his debut on 9 January 2019, coming on as a substitute in a 3–0 victory over [[CD Leganés|Leganés]] in the [[2018–19 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46790045|title=Real Madrid 3–0 Leganés|work=BBC Sport |access-date=9 January 2019|archive-date=14 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414214728/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46790045|url-status=live}}</ref> His league debut came four days later, when he again came in as a substitute in a 2–1 win over [[Real Betis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2019/01/13/5c3bb3c746163f89798b4582.html|title=Ceballos rescues Real Madrid in Seville|newspaper=Marca|date=13 January 2019 |location=Spain|access-date=13 January 2019|archive-date=13 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113005338/https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2019/01/13/5c3bb3c746163f89798b4582.html|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first goal on 12 May 2019, in a 1–3 defeat at [[Real Sociedad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2019/05/12/5cd85926268e3ee7488b45f3.html|title=Brahim Diaz impresses again with a stunning solo goal|newspaper=Marca|date=12 May 2019 |location=Spain|access-date=12 May 2019|archive-date=12 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512183450/https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2019/05/12/5cd85926268e3ee7488b45f3.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

He made six appearances during the league season, as Real Madrid won the [[2019–20 La Liga]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2020/07/17/5f10db2146163f3c2c8b45d7.html|title=Real Madrid win the longest LaLiga Santander season|date=17 July 2020|access-date=17 July 2020|newspaper=Marca|location=Spain|archive-date=17 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200717031601/https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2020/07/17/5f10db2146163f3c2c8b45d7.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

====2020–23: Loan to AC Milan and Serie A champion====
On 4 September 2020, Real Madrid announced that Brahim would be loaned out to [[AC Milan]] for the duration of the [[2020–21 AC Milan season|2020–21 season]].<ref>{{cite press release|url = https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2020/09/04/official-announcement-brahim|title = Official Announcement: Brahim|publisher = Real Madrid CF|date = 4 September 2020|access-date = 4 September 2020|archive-date = 5 September 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200905150600/https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2020/09/04/official-announcement-brahim|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |url = https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/articles/media/2020-09-04/official-statement-brahim-diaz |title = Official Statement: Brahim Díaz |publisher = AC Milan |date = 4 September 2020 |access-date = 4 September 2020 |archive-date = 4 September 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200904172831/https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/articles/media/2020-09-04/official-statement-brahim-diaz |url-status = live }}</ref> On 27 September, he scored his first goal in a 2–0 away win over [[F.C. Crotone|Crotone]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/crotone-vs-milan/cronica/2020/09/27/5f70dcdf46163f060a8b4577.html |title=Brahim opens his account as AC Milan beat Crotone |website=Marca |location=Spain |date=27 September 2020 |access-date=13 May 2021 |archive-date=9 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221109184701/https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/crotone-vs-milan/cronica/2020/09/27/5f70dcdf46163f060a8b4577.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On 9 May 2021, he scored a goal in a 3–0 away win over [[Juventus FC|Juventus]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2021/may/10/juventus-suffer-another-humiliation-as-milan-halt-their-own-slump-serie-a |title=Juventus suffer another humiliation as Milan halt their own slump |website=The Guardian |date=10 May 2021 |access-date=13 May 2021 |archive-date=9 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221109184659/https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2021/may/10/juventus-suffer-another-humiliation-as-milan-halt-their-own-slump-serie-a |url-status=live }}</ref> After the 2020–21 season, he was loaned for another two years to AC Milan with a buyout option.<ref>{{cite web|date=19 July 2021|title=Official statement: Brahim Díaz|url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/articles/media/2021-07-19/official-statement-brahim-diaz|website=acmilan.com|access-date=19 July 2021|archive-date=23 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210723154353/https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/articles/media/2021-07-19/official-statement-brahim-diaz|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=19 July 2021|title=Official Announcement: Brahim|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2021/07/19/official-announcement-brahim|publisher=Real Madrid C.F.|access-date=19 July 2021|archive-date=19 July 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210719165811/https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2021/07/19/official-announcement-brahim|url-status=live}}</ref> On 15 September 2021, he scored his first Champions League goal against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in a 3–2 defeat in the [[2021–22 UEFA Champions League|2021–22 Champions League]] group stage.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Liverpool comeback sinks Milan in epic|language=en-GB|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58561430|access-date=15 September 2021|archive-date=6 October 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211006200114/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58561430|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 8 October 2022, Brahim scored his second goal against Juventus in a [[2022–23 Serie A|league game]], finishing after a run to double the advantage as he seized a loose pass and knocked it around the Juventus defender [[Leonardo Bonucci]] to get through on goal, and then finished past goalkeeper [[Wojciech Szczęsny]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=AC Milan 2–0 Juventus – Fikayo Tomori, Brahim Diaz both score as Milan cruise to victory against Juve |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/serie-a/2022-2023/live-ac-milan-juventus_mtc1363670/live-commentary.shtml |access-date=15 February 2023 |website=Eurosport |language=en}}</ref>

On 14 February 2023, he scored the only goal in a 1–0 victory over [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in the [[2022–23 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League round of 16]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Milan 1–0 Tottenham: Brahim Díaz heads hosts to victory |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/027e-17506d36e534-7af5dcb16051-1000--milan-1-0-tottenham-brahim-diaz-heads-hosts-to-victory/ |publisher=UEFA |date=14 February 2023 |access-date=14 February 2023 |archive-date=14 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230214224622/https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/027e-17506d36e534-7af5dcb16051-1000--milan-1-0-tottenham-brahim-diaz-heads-hosts-to-victory/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Tottenham fall to narrow first-leg loss at Milan |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64632017 |access-date=15 February 2023 |archive-date=15 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230215002547/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64632017 |url-status=live }}</ref>

====2023–present: Return to Real Madrid====
On 10 June 2023, Real Madrid announced Brahim's return from a three-season loan at AC Milan, and upon his return, he signed a contract extension with the club until June 2027, succeeding the departing [[Marco Asensio]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 June 2023 |title=Official Announcement: Brahim Díaz |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2023/06/10/official-announcement-brahim-diaz |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230610120240/https://www.realmadrid.com/en/news/2023/06/10/official-announcement-brahim-diaz |archive-date=10 June 2023 |access-date=9 November 2023 |website= |publisher=[[Real Madrid CF]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Cortegana |first=Mario |title=Real Madrid tie Diaz to new contract until 2027 |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4599044/2023/06/10/real-madrid-brahim-diaz-contract-2/ |access-date=10 June 2023 |archive-date=10 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230610121147/https://theathletic.com/4599044/2023/06/10/real-madrid-tie-brahim-diaz-to-new-contract-until-2027/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 27 September, he scored his first goal since his return, contributing to a 2–0 triumph over [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]] during a La Liga game at the [[Santiago Bernabéu Stadium|Santiago Bernabéu]]. He was subsequently awarded the Man of the Match title.<ref>{{Cite news |date=27 September 2023 |title=La Liga: Real Madrid vs Las Palmas |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/live/football/66939746 |access-date=27 September 2023}}</ref> On 8 November, he scored his first Champions League goal for Real Madrid, by netting the opener in a 3–0 victory over [[S.C. Braga|Braga]], which secured his club's qualification to the knockout phase.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/687597 |title=Real Madrid beat Braga to clinch Champions League last-16 place |publisher=ESPN |date=8 November 2023 }}</ref>

On 6 January 2024, Brahim scored his first [[Copa del Rey]] goal in a match against [[Arandina CF|Arandina]], contributing to a 3–1 victory for Real Madrid.<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 January 2024 |title=Real Madrid 3–1 Arandina (Jan 6, 2024) Game Analysis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/690924 |access-date=7 January 2024 |website=ESPN |language=en |archive-date=7 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240107061626/https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/690924 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[2023–24 Supercopa de España|Supercopa de España]] semi-final on 10 January at [[KSU Stadium (Riyadh)|KSU Stadium]] in Riyadh, Brahim clinched a dramatic victory for Real Madrid over [[Atlético Madrid]] with a last-minute goal, making the score 5–3 in a match that extended into extra time.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 January 2024 |title=CRÓNICA {{!}} El Real Madrid peleará por el título tras imponerse en una vibrante semifinal (5–3) |url=https://rfef.es/es/noticias/cronica-el-real-madrid-peleara-por-el-titulo-tras-imponerse-en-una-vibrante-semifinal-5-3 |access-date=11 January 2024 |website=[[Real Federación Española de Fútbol]] |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=10 January 2024 |title=Madrid reach Spanish Super Cup final after epic semi win |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en-US/news/football/first-team/reports/10-01-2024 |access-date=11 January 2024 |website=Real Madrid CF |language=en-US}}</ref> His decisive goal came as Atlético's goalkeeper [[Jan Oblak]] advanced for a corner, staying in Real Madrid's half after a throw-in, allowing Brahim to score from just inside the halfway line and secure Real Madrid's place in the final.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 January 2024 |title=Real Madrid 5–3 Atletico Madrid – Late show as Los Blancos score twice in extra-time, make final of Spanish Super Cup |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/spanish-supercopa/2023-2024/real-madrid-v-atletico-madrid-spanish-supercopa-live_sto9948827/story.shtml |access-date=11 January 2024 |website=Eurosport |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=10 January 2024 |title=Brahim y el golazo que sentenció la Semi de la Supercopa para el Real Madrid |url=https://www.marca.com/mx/futbol/la-liga/2024/01/10/659f1a36e2704eb5838b45d4.html |access-date=11 January 2024 |website=Marca México |language=es-MX}}</ref>

A month later, on 13 February, in the [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|Champions League round of 16]] first leg match, Brahim scored the only goal for Real Madrid against [[RB Leipzig]] at the [[Red Bull Arena (Leipzig)|Red Bull Arena]],<ref>{{Cite news |date=13 February 2024 |title=Superb Diaz strike earns Real Madrid win at Leipzig |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68268572 |access-date=14 February 2024 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> securing a 1–0 victory with a left-footed curler past Leipzig goalkeeper [[Péter Gulácsi]] after skilfully evading multiple defenders, earning him the Man of the Match award in a compound accomplishment.<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 February 2024 |title=Brahim stunner makes it advantage Madrid in the tie |url=https://www.realmadrid.com/en-US/news/football/first-team/reports/13-02-2024 |access-date=14 February 2024 |website=Real Madrid CF |language=en-US}}</ref>

On 11 May 2024, Brahim scored a brace in a 4–0 victory over [[Granada CF|Granada]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=11 May 2024 |title=Granada vs Real Madrid: Spanish La Liga |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c3g8y7jrp19t |access-date=12 May 2024 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> A month later, he won the Champions League with his club following a 2–0 victory over [[Borussia Dortmund]] in the [[2024 UEFA Champions League final|final]], becoming the third Moroccan to achieve this feat after [[Achraf Hakimi]] and [[Hakim Ziyech]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africanfootball.com/news/816409/Diaz-becomes-third-Moroccan-to-win-Champions-League |title=Diaz becomes third Moroccan to win Champions League |publisher=African Football |date=2 June 2024 }}</ref>

==International career==
===Spain===
Brahim was a youth international for Spain, and made his first appearances at age 16, where he received praise for his performances for Spain U17 in the [[2016 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]].<ref name="MCOP" /> Due to the isolation of some national team players following the positive [[COVID-19]] test of [[Sergio Busquets]], Spain's under-21 squad were called up for the international friendly match against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] on 8 June 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sefutbol.com/oficial-lista-convocados-encuentro-lituania |title=Oficial {{!}} Lista de convocados para el encuentro ante Lituania |trans-title=Official {{!}} Squad list for the match against Lithuania |publisher=[[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] |date=6 June 2021 |access-date=7 June 2021 |language=es |archive-date=8 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211008070336/https://sefutbol.com/oficial-lista-convocados-encuentro-lituania |url-status=dead }}</ref> Díaz made his senior debut in the match and scored the second goal in a 4–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/espana-vs-lituania/cronica/2021/06/08/60bfd85222601dc65d8b458f.html|title=Spain youngsters impress in Lithuania rout|newspaper=Marca|location=Spain|date=8 June 2021|accessdate=8 June 2021|archive-date=10 June 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210610015358/https://www.marca.com/en/football/international-football/espana-vs-lituania/cronica/2021/06/08/60bfd85222601dc65d8b458f.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Morocco===
[[File:Brahim Diaz 3 vs Niger (cropped) (cropped).jpg|thumb|283x283px|Brahim with [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] in a match against [[Niger national football team|Niger]] in 2025]]
On 27 January 2023, it was announced that Brahim planned to switch allegiances to the [[Morocco national football team|Morocco national team]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Brahim Diaz to change his international allegiance despite scoring on Spain debut |url=https://www.sportbible.com/football/brahim-diaz-international-change-spain-morocco-789285-20230126 |access-date=27 January 2023 |website=Sport Bible|date=26 January 2023|archive-date=27 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230127030403/https://www.sportbible.com/football/brahim-diaz-international-change-spain-morocco-789285-20230126 |url-status=live }}</ref> In October, ''[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]'' reported that he had decided to represent Morocco, with some administrative details related to change in nationality being resolved.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2023/10/11/65261b0ae2704ed7b28b458b.html |title=Real Madrid player chooses to make switch to represent Morocco over Spain |publisher=Marca |date=10 October 2023 |access-date=12 October 2023 |archive-date=12 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231012082207/https://www.marca.com/en/football/real-madrid/2023/10/11/65261b0ae2704ed7b28b458b.html |url-status=live }}</ref> However, Díaz was not called up by coach [[Walid Regragui]] for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]] due to a pre-established agreement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingfut.com/2024/02/08/regragui-brahim-diaz-morocco/ |title=Regragui to meet up with Brahim Diaz to represent Morocco |first=Ali |last=Ismail Gaballah |website=Kingfut |date=8 February 2024 }}</ref>

On 10 March 2024, ''Marca'' reported that Díaz had officially informed the [[Royal Moroccan Football Federation]] that he would be switching his allegiance to their national team.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 March 2024 |title=Brahim elige jugar con Marruecos ante la pasividad de España |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/real-madrid/2024/03/10/65e37c1ce2704e19708b4593.html |access-date=13 March 2024|newspaper=Marca|language=es}}</ref> On 13 March, Díaz was called up by the Morocco coach Walid Regragui for the matches against [[Angola national football team|Angola]] and [[Mauritania national football team|Mauritania]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 March 2024|script-title=ar:السيد وليد الركراكي يستدعي 24 لاعبا لمباراتي أنغولا وموريتانيا |trans-title=Mr. Walid Regragui summons 24 players for the matches between Angola and Mauritania |url=https://frmf.ma/%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b3%d9%8a%d8%af-%d9%88%d9%84%d9%8a%d8%af-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b1%d9%83%d8%b1%d8%a7%d9%83%d9%8a-%d9%8a%d8%b3%d8%aa%d8%af%d8%b9%d9%8a-24-%d9%84%d8%a7%d8%b9%d8%a8%d8%a7-%d9%84%d9%85%d8%a8%d8%a7/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313225659/https://frmf.ma/%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D9%88%D9%84%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%83%D9%8A-%D9%8A%D8%B3%D8%AA%D8%AF%D8%B9%D9%8A-24-%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%A8%D8%A7-%D9%84%D9%85%D8%A8%D8%A7/ |archive-date=13 March 2024 |access-date=13 March 2024|publisher=[[Royal Moroccan Football Federation]] |language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=13 March 2024 |title=Real Madrid's Diaz to represent Morocco |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/real-madrids-diaz-represent-morocco-2024-03-13/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313224520/https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/real-madrids-diaz-represent-morocco-2024-03-13/ |archive-date=13 March 2024 |access-date=13 March 2024|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> He made his debut on 22 March in a 1–0 victory against Angola.<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 March 2024|first=Jihanne|last=Rahhou|title=Brahim Diaz Says His Debut for Morocco Was 'A Very Special Day'|url=https://www.moroccoworldnews.com/2024/03/21730/brahim-diaz-says-his-debut-for-morocco-was-a-very-special-day/|website=[[Morocco World News]]|access-date=22 June 2025}}</ref> On 6 September, Díaz scored his first goal for Morocco in a 4–1 victory against [[Gabon national football team|Gabon]] during the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]]. On 15 November, he scored his first brace for Morocco in a 5–1 qualification win over Gabon.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Senoussi |first=Zoubida |date=15 November 2024 |title=Elim CAN 2025 : Le Maroc s'impose largement face au Gabon avec notamment un doublé de Diaz (5–1) |url=https://fr.hespress.com/396544-elim-can-2025-le-maroc-simpose-largement-face-au-gabon-avec-notamment-un-double-de-diaz-5-1.html |access-date=15 November 2024 |website=Hespress Français|language=fr}}</ref> Three days later, Díaz scored his first [[hat-trick]] in a 7–0 victory against [[Lesotho national football team|Lesotho]] during the final match of the African qualifications.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Darouiche|first=Mohamed |date=18 November 2024 |title=Elim CAN 2025 : Le Maroc pulvérise le Lesotho |url=https://fr.hespress.com/396894-elim-can-2025-le-maroc-pulverise-le-lesotho.html |access-date=18 November 2024 |website=Hespress Français|language=fr}}</ref>

In October 2025, Brahim's Morocco broke the [[List of world association football records|world record for the longest winning streak in international football]], surpassing [[Spain national football team|Spain]]'s previous mark of 15 consecutive victories. With a 1–0 win over [[Congo national football team|Congo]] in [[Rabat]], they extended their unbeaten run to 16.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gleeson |first=Mark |date=14 October 2025 |title=Morocco beat Congo to surpass Spain's wins record |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/morocco-beat-congo-surpass-spains-wins-record-2025-10-14/ |access-date=15 October 2025 |website=Reuters}}</ref> Their winning streak ultimately reached 19 consecutive wins before coming to an end during the 2025 AFCON with a 1–1 draw against [[Mali national football team|Mali]] in the second group stage match.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-12-27 |title=Morocco's historic winning streak snapped by Mali |url=https://global.espn.com/football/story/_/id/47422160/morocco-historic-winning-streak-snapped-mali |access-date=2025-12-31 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref>

Diaz was named in the Morocco squad for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]] on home soil, where he scored the tournament's opening goal in a 2–0 victory over [[Comoros national football team|Comoros]], earning the Man of the Match award. He scored in the subsequent group matches against Mali and [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]] becoming the first Moroccan to score in every group stage match since [[Ahmed Faras]] in [[1976 African Cup of Nations|1976]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Brahim Díaz stellt historische Bestmarke auf – und gibt Real Madrid wichtige Zusage |url=https://www.fussballeuropa.com/news/brahim-diaz-stellt-historische-bestmarke-auf-und-gibt-real-madrid-wichtige-zusage-2025-12 |access-date=2025-12-30 |website=Fussball Europa |language=de}}</ref> On 4 January 2026, he scored the only goal against [[Tanzania national football team|Tanzania]] in the round of 16, becoming the first Moroccan player ever to score four goals in four consecutive AFCON matches, and was named Man of the Match.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Miller|first=Ben|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cj6w2767d46t|title=Afcon 2025: Morocco 1-0 Tanzania - Brahim Diaz fires hosts into last eight|date=4 January 2026|website=BBC Sport|access-date=6 January 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/africa-cup-of-nations/articles/brahim-d%C3%ADaz-makes-afcon-history-as-morocco-edge-past-tanzania-2026-01-04 |title=Brahim Díaz Makes AFCON History as Morocco Edge Past Tanzania |publisher=beIN SPORTS |date=4 January 2026 }}</ref> On 18 January, he missed a [[panenka penalty]] in the last minute of stoppage time in the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations final|AFCON final]] against [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]], after a 15 minute protest by the Senegalese team against the referee's decision in which the team left the field. The match ended in a 1–0 defeat after extra time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/senegal-vs-morocco-afcon-2025-final-score-result/DQtU75DqxAoW/ |title=Senegal beat Morocco thanks to Gueye strike in extraordinary AFCON 2025 final: Live updates and reaction |work=The New York Times |date=19 January 2026 }}</ref> However, he concluded the tournament as top scorer with five goals in total.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/brahim-diaz-wins-totalenergies-caf-afcon-2025-puma-golden-boot/ |title=Brahim Díaz wins TotalEnergies CAF AFCON 2025 Puma Golden Boot |publisher=CAF Online |date=18 January 2026 }}</ref> [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] later overturned the on-field result due to Senegal's forfeit: On March 17, 2026, the CAF Appeal Board ruled that Senegal had forfeited the final through their temporary walk-off (deemed a breach of regulations, including Article 84 of the AFCON rules), awarding Morocco a 3–0 victory on default and declaring the Atlas Lions the official champions of the 2025 Africa Cup of Nations.<ref name="AFCON"/>

==Style of play==
Brahim Díaz is an ambidextrous and technically gifted [[attacking midfielder]], known for his [[dribbling]] ability, agility, and playmaking ability. He prefers to play as a number 10, but can also play as a [[Midfielder|winger]] on either one of the flanks.

